Data Acquisition and Plotting tests

Data Download

q <- readNWISdv(siteNumbers = '06752260',
                parameterCd = '00060',
                startDate = '2017-01-01',
                endDate = '2022-01-01') %>%
  rename(q = 'X_00060_00003')

Static Data Plotter

ggplot(q, aes(x = Date, y = q)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  ylab('Q (cfs)') + 
  ggtitle('Discharge in the Poudre River, Fort Collins')

Interactive Data Plotter

q_xts <- xts(q$q, order.by = q$Date)


dygraph(q_xts, main = "Discharge in the Poudre River, Fort Collins, CO") %>%
  dyAxis("y", label = "Discharge (cfs)")

DyGraph example

Interact with this chart!

dygraph(q_xts, main = "Discharge in the Poudre River, Fort Collins, CO") %>%
  dyAxis("y", label = "Discharge (cfs)") %>%
  dyOptions(drawPoints = TRUE, pointSize = 2)

Poudre Paragraph

The Cache la Poudre River in Larimer County, Colorado is one of 55 designated National Heritage Areas in the United States. The river showcases historical developments built by early Euro-American settlers, a popular trail system which follows the river through Fort Collins, and miles of natural beauty which, despite increasing human development, remains prime wildlife habitat. The Bird Conservancy of the Rockies has organized a community science project to study Eastern Screech-Owls along the Cache la Poudre River in Fort Collins and is currently seeking volunteer surveyors for the period March to mid-May. For those interested in the water flow dynamics of the river, there are several stream gauges maintained by Colorado Division of Water Resources with open access to data.
